% ====================================================================
% test_phase3_mailbox_global.trx -- VM Redux Phase 3 invariants
% ====================================================================
% After Phase 3, MailboxHeader is allocated from global VM via
% gvm_alloc<MailboxHeader>(total, ChunkKind::Mailbox).  The mailbox
% is BASE-immune to save/restore, and the per-save-level pool is
% collapsed to a class-indexed-only pool.  Three invariants:
%
%   I1. Allocating a mailbox bumps /by-kind/mailbox.
%   I2. An above-barrier actor's mailbox does NOT leak across
%       restore -- coroutine_kill -> coroutine_cleanup_mailbox ->
%       mailbox_recycle parks it back in the pool, where the next
%       same-class spawn reuses the same offset.
%   I3. A surviving actor's blocked-sender list is correctly
%       scrubbed of dying senders (Hazard #1) -- after restore,
%       the blocked-sender chain only contains live coroutines
%       (or nulloffset).
%
% Note: actors mostly use yield-driven scheduling.  Each section
% interleaves coroutine-sleep so the actor and any senders get a
% chance to run.
% ====================================================================

% rt-ok counts failures in a restore-immune slot -- string byte writes
% are unjournaled, so the count survives assertions made inside save
% scopes, and the 1-byte string lives in LOCAL VM, invisible to the
% global-heap/gc-counter probes some files assert on.  The file THROWS
% at EOF: test_all counts a file as failed only when its run throws,
% so print-only failures would slip the suite verdict.
/rt-fails 1 string def
rt-fails 0 16#0#b put
/rt-ok { exch { = } { (FAILED: ) print = rt-fails 0  rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 1 add dup 255 gt { pop 255 } if /byte-type cast  put } if-else } def
/yield-many { 0 1 29 { pop 0 coroutine-sleep } for } def

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 1: mailbox allocation lands in /by-kind/mailbox
% ====================================================================
% A fresh actor-spawn allocates a MailboxHeader via gvm_alloc tagged
% ChunkKind::Mailbox.  /by-kind/mailbox count goes up by 1.

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /pre1 exch def

[ { 0 coroutine-sleep coroutine-die } actor-spawn pop
yield-many

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /post1 exch def
post1 pre1 sub 1 ge   (s1: mailbox count +>=1 after actor-spawn)  rt-ok

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 2: above-barrier actor's mailbox is recycled, not leaked
% ====================================================================
% Spawn an actor inside a save scope; restore.  The actor dies via
% coroutine_kill (above-barrier coroutine reclaim path), which runs
% coroutine_cleanup_mailbox -> mailbox_recycle.  The mailbox returns
% to the pool, NOT abandoned.
%
% Verification: spawn a SECOND actor at the same default capacity
% after restore, then check that /by-kind/mailbox count is bounded
% (the pool reused the original mailbox slot).

% Drain to a steady state first.
yield-many

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /pre2 exch def

save /sv2 exch def
[ { 0 coroutine-sleep coroutine-die } actor-spawn pop
yield-many
sv2 restore

% After restore, allocate a fresh actor.  If the recycler worked, the
% global-mailbox count should NOT permanently grow.  We allow at most
% 1 above the pre2 baseline (the new actor's mailbox; the old one is
% in the pool ready for reuse, doesn't increase the live block count).
yield-many

[ { 0 coroutine-sleep coroutine-die } actor-spawn pop
yield-many

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /post2 exch def
% Strict bound: after one save/spawn/restore + one fresh spawn, the
% delta from pre2 must be at most 1 (the live new actor's mailbox).
% A delta of 2+ would mean the recycled mailbox was abandoned.
post2 pre2 sub 1 le   (s2: mailbox not leaked across restore)    rt-ok

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 3: surviving actor's blocked-sender list scrubbed after restore
% ====================================================================
% Setup: long-lived actor A at outer scope.  Inside save scope, fill
% A's mailbox to capacity, then have an extra sender block on it.
% Restore.  The blocked sender is killed by restore; A's mailbox
% (global, surviving) must have its blocked-sender list scrubbed by
% mailbox_scrub_above_barrier.  Verify A is still functional and no
% stale offsets remain.

yield-many

% Spawn A with capacity 2 so we can fill it quickly.
[ { { actor-receive pop } loop } 2 actor-spawn-capacity /actorA exch def
yield-many

save /sv3 exch def

% Fill A's mailbox to capacity (2 messages) without giving A a chance
% to drain.  We achieve "no drain" by NOT yielding from main between
% sends -- main doesn't yield, A doesn't run.
1 actorA actor-send
2 actorA actor-send
% Mailbox full.  Spawn an extra sender that will block.
[ { 99 actorA actor-send } coroutine-launch /sender exch def
% Yield once so sender can run, fill, and block on the full mailbox.
0 coroutine-sleep
% sender is now Sleeping/Blocked, sitting on actorA->m_blocked_sender list.

sv3 restore

% After restore: sender's CoroutineContext is above barrier and was
% killed.  actorA's mailbox is in global VM, survives.  Its
% m_blocked_sender list should have been scrubbed.
%
% Verify A is still alive and can receive a fresh message.
yield-many

42 actorA actor-send
yield-many

% Cleanup: kill A.
actorA coroutine-kill
yield-many

% If we got here without an InternalError or stale-offset crash, the
% scrub did its job.
true (s3: surviving actor's mailbox functional after restore + scrub) rt-ok

% ====================================================================
% SECTION 4: mailbox lives in global VM (BASE-immune)
% ====================================================================
% The mailbox count after a deep save/restore cycle should match the
% pre-cycle count plus the live actors' allocations.  No "the pool
% died on restore" leak.

yield-many

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /pre4 exch def

% Three nested save/restore cycles, each spawning + killing an actor.
3 1 1 {
    pop
    save /sv-loop exch def
    [ { coroutine-die } actor-spawn pop
    yield-many
    sv-loop restore
} for
yield-many

vm-global-info /by-kind get /mailbox get /count get /post4 exch def
% Bounded growth: the pool absorbs the recycled mailboxes.  Allow a
% small delta for any transient slack from the loop's frame dicts.
post4 pre4 sub 3 le   (s4: 3 spawn/restore cycles bounded growth)  rt-ok

rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 0 gt { /rt-assertions-failed throw } if
(test_phase3_mailbox_global: ALL TESTS PASSED) =
(__test_ok__) =
